---
import VizPlaceholder from '../../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section
  id="single-repo"
  class="border-y border-neutral-900 bg-neutral-900/40 px-6 py-20 md:py-28"
>
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl">
    <div class="max-w-3xl">
      <h2
        class="text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
      >
        A harness lives inside one repo
      </h2>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 grid items-center gap-12 lg:grid-cols-2">
      <div class="space-y-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
        <p>
          Point a harness at a repository and it is remarkably capable inside
          it. It reads the code, runs the tests, makes the change, opens the
          PR. Within those walls it can act on almost anything.
        </p>
        <p>
          But everything it sees, everything it touches, and everything it
          remembers <mark>ends at the repo boundary</mark>. The repository is
          the harness's whole world. That is not an accident or a flaw: the
          repo is the unit a harness is built to understand, the same way React
          was built to render components and nothing more.
        </p>
        <p class="text-neutral-400">
          Which was perfectly fine, as long as your work fit inside one repo
          too.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <VizPlaceholder
          label="SingleRepoCube island: one frontend repo cube, AI agent glowing inside, hard boundary"
          ratio="aspect-[4/3]"
        />
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
